            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-222-person2045">
                  JOHN 
                  BALLARD
               <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2045" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2045" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2045" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18290910-222-viclabel1225" type="occupation">labourer and a green-grocer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-222-victim2044 t18290910-222-viclabel1225"></join>, and live at <placeName id="t18290910-222-crimeloc1226">Brockley-hill, Little Stanmore</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-222-crimeloc1226" type="placeName" value="Brockley-hill, Little Stanmore"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290910-222-crimeloc1226" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-222-off1223 t18290910-222-crimeloc1226"></join>. On the 21st of August, in the afternoon, I turned my gelding out on Brockley-hill, within a quarter of a mile of my house, on a waste - I saw him still grazing there a little after eight o'clock that evening, I went to look for him between four and five next morning, Saturday, and he was gone - I searched for him on Saturday and Sunday, and found him on Monday, about twelve, at Monk's stables, near Whitechapel; it was mine - I have seen the prisoner once or twice in different parts of the neighbourhood, but not to know him - I live about twelve miles from town.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-222-person2046">
                  CHARLES 
                  RICH
               <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2046" type="surname" value="RICH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2046" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2046" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am clerk to 
               <persName id="t18290910-222-person2047">
                  William 
                  Monk
               <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2047" type="surname" value="Monk"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2047" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2047" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , a horse-slaughterer, in Whitechapel-road, opposite the London-hospital. On Saturday, the 22nd of August, about half-past nine o'clock in the morning, a horse was brought to me by the prisoner; another man, whom I have known in the neighbourhood for fifteen years, was with him - the man who came with him said I was to give this man 30s. for the horse, and 1s. to him, for shewing him the slaughtering-house; I put a sovereign and a half into the prisoner's hand; I had scarcely done that, before I said to the other man."Why, do you know this man who has brought the horse?" he said he did not; I then said to the prisoner, "Give me my money back again, I have strong donbts on my mind that this is not right;" he immediately gave me back the money - I told him I should detain the horse and money - Mr. Monk was standing in the shed close by; he took him into the counting-house, and questioned him; he was perfectly satisfied that it was not correct, and told me to take him to the office; as we went along, he made a start, and attempted to escape; I, however secured him, and told him it was a folly to put himself in jeopardy for so trifling a thing; he said he had taken the horse from Mr. Wright, of King's Langley, who was a wealthy man, and could well afford to lose it - I took him to Lambeth-street; he said he was a poor man, and had taken the horse out of the field - we wrote that evening to Wright, of King's Langley, but got no answer - it is near Hemel Hempstead.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I told him no such thing; I said I was afraid it was a stolen horse, not that I had stolen it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-222-person2048">
                  JOHN 
                  BALLARD
               <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2048" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2048" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-person2048" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . King's Langley is below Watford; a great many miles from me.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I had been down at harvest-work, and as I came back on Saturday morning, I met a man in the road with this horse; he asked if I wished to buy it; I said, "I don't care, what do you ask for it?" he asked 35s.; I said, "I have 28s.;" he agreed to take it. I have witnesses who saw me buy the horse, and pay the money, if I had an opportunity of bringing them here.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290910-222-verdict1227" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-verdict1227" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs> - <rs id="t18290910-222-punish1228" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290910-222-punish1228" type="punishmentCategory" value="death"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-222-defend2042 t18290910-222-punish1228"></join>
               DEATH
            </rs>. Aged 58.</p>
               <p>There was another indictment against the prisoner for a like offence.</p>
